Grocery shopping has become even more stressful with rising food prices linked to fuel price hikes. AgriSA Executive Director, Christo van der Rheede discussed this with eNCA's Tumelo Mothoatone. Courtesy if #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Farmers are pleading with government to intervene in rising fuel costs. Price hikes increase production costs which are then passed on to consumers. READ: R17-billion budget to support food security in SA AgriSA Executive Director, Christo van Der Rheede, says the intervention is urgently needed. "We called on on government to consider increasing the diesel rebate. South African farmers do not get production support like the Chinese, European, United States, and Brazilian counterparts. READ: Cosatu: Fuel levy reduction not enough "We have to survive on the diesel rebate that government provides," he said. "Increasing that will bring much needed relief and enable farmers to expand the hectares that they are expected to plant."